# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aerodynamics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] Roshko was born in Bellevue, Alberta in the Dominion of Canada in 1923.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] He completed his undergraduate education at the University of Alberta, where he earned a B.Sc. degree in Engineering Physics in 1945.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] After a brief tour in the Royal Canadian Artillery, he moved to Caltech's Guggenheim Aeronautical Laboratory, where he earned an M.Sc. degree in 1947 and a Ph.D. in 1952.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] Liepmann and wrote a thesis on turbulence in vortex wakes.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] As a graduate student, he conducted research through the National Advisory Committee on Aeronautics (NACA), the predecessor to NASA.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] Roshko spent his career at Caltech, beginning as a research fellow in 1952 and a senior fellow in 1954.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] He was appointed assistant professor in 1958 and attained tenure in 1958 before becoming a full professor in 1962.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] Roshko was named von Kármán Professor in 1985 and retired in 1994.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] He served as director of the Guggenheim Aeronautical Laboratory (GALCIT) from 1985 to 1987.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] In the decades following 1952, he was regarded as a seminal fluid dynamics theorist, modeler, and experimentalist.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] Roshko is known for his contributions to gas dynamics and turbulence using high-speed imaging.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] He co-authored the widely used textbook *Elements of Gasdynamics* with his former advisor, Hans W.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] He made influential research contributions to problems of flow separation, bluff-body aerodynamics, and the structure of turbulent shear flow.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] He also studied shock wave–boundary layer interactions using shock tube technology.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] Apart from scientific research, he was a consultant for the Office of Naval Research and companies including McDonnell Douglas, Rockwell International, and General Motors.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] In 1970, he helped organize the Wind Engineering Research Council and served on its executive board until 1983.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] Roshko was an elected member of the National Academy of Sciences and National Academy of Engineering.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] He was a fellow of the American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics (AIAA), the American Physical Society (APS), the Canadian Aeronautics and Space Institute, the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, and an Honorary Fellow of the Indian Academy of Sciences.
[src:aerodynamics/a-roshko] He died in his home in Altadena, California, in 2017, aged 93.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In fluid dynamics, **drag**, sometimes referred to as **fluid resistance**, and also known as **viscous force**, is a force acting opposite to the direction of motion of any object moving with respect to a surrounding fluid.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] This can exist between two fluid layers, or between a fluid and a solid surface.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Drag forces tend to decrease fluid velocity relative to the solid object in the fluid's path.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Unlike other resistive forces, drag force depends on velocity.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Drag force is proportional to the relative velocity for low-speed flow and is proportional to the velocity squared for high-speed flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] This distinction between low and high-speed flow is measured by the Reynolds number.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] There are many distinct types of drag caused by different physical interactions between the object and fluid.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Last, in aerodynamics the term "parasitic drag" is often used.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Parasitic drag is the sum of form drag and skin friction drag and is entirely negative to an aircraft, in contrast with lift-induced drag which is a consequence of generating lift.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The effect of streamlining on the relative proportions of skin friction and form drag is shown in the table at right for an airfoil, which is a streamlined body, and a cylinder, which is a bluff body.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Also shown is a flat plate in two different orientations, illustrating the effect of orientation on the relative proportions of skin friction and form drag, and showing the pressure difference between front and back.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] A body is known as bluff or blunt when the source of drag is dominated by pressure forces, and streamlined if the drag is dominated by viscous forces.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] For example, road vehicles are bluff bodies.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] For aircraft, pressure and friction drag are included in the definition of parasitic drag.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Parasite drag is often expressed in terms of a hypothetical.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] With other parameters remaining the same, as the lift generated by a body increases, so does the lift-induced drag.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] This means that as the wing's angle of attack increases (up to a maximum called the stalling angle), the lift coefficient also increases, and so too does the lift-induced drag.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] At the onset of stall, lift is abruptly decreased, as is lift-induced drag, but viscous pressure drag, a component of parasite drag, increases due to the formation of turbulent unattached flow in the wake behind the body.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] For an aircraft at low speed, induced drag tends to be relatively greater than parasitic drag because a high angle of attack is required to maintain lift, increasing induced drag.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] As speed increases, the angle of attack is reduced and the induced drag decreases.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Parasitic drag, however, increases because the fluid is flowing more quickly around protruding objects increasing friction or drag.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] At even higher speeds (transonic), wave drag enters the picture.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Each of these forms of drag changes in proportion to the others based on speed.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The combined overall drag curve therefore shows a minimum at some airspeed - an aircraft flying at this speed will be at or close to its optimal efficiency.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Pilots will use this speed to maximize endurance (minimum fuel consumption), or maximize gliding range in the event of an engine failure.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The equivalent parasite area is the area which a flat plate perpendicular to the flow would have to match the parasite drag of an aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] It is a measure used when comparing the drag of different aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] For example, the Douglas DC-3 has an equivalent parasite area of 2.20 m2 (23.7 ft2) and the McDonnell Douglas DC-9, with 30 years of advancement in aircraft design, an area of 1.91 m2 (20.6 ft2) although it carried five times as many passengers.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Drag depends on the properties of the fluid and on the size, shape, and speed of the object.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The graph to the right shows how $C_{\rm {D}}$ varies with $\mathrm {Re}$ for the case of a sphere.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Since the power needed to overcome the drag force is the product of the force times speed, the power needed to overcome drag will vary as the square of the speed at low Reynolds numbers, and as the cube of the speed at high numbers.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] It can be demonstrated that drag force can be expressed as a function of a dimensionless number, which is dimensionally identical to the Bejan number.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Consequently, drag force and drag coefficient can be a function of Bejan number.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] As mentioned, the drag equation with a constant drag coefficient gives the force moving through a fluid at a relatively large velocity, i.e. high Reynolds number, Re > ~1000.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The reference area *A* is often the orthographic projection of the object, or the *frontal area,* on a plane perpendicular to the direction of motion.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] For objects with a simple shape, such as a sphere, this is the cross sectional area.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Sometimes a body is a composite of different parts, each with a different reference area (drag coefficient corresponding to each of those different areas must be determined).
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In the case of a **wing**, the reference areas are the same, and the drag force is in the same ratio as the lift force.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Therefore, the reference for a wing is often the lifting area, sometimes referred to as "wing area" rather than the frontal area.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] For an object with a smooth surface, and non-fixed separation points (like a sphere or circular cylinder), the drag coefficient may vary with Reynolds number *Re*, up to extremely high values (*Re* of the order 107).
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] For an object with well-defined fixed separation points, like a circular disk with its plane normal to the flow direction, the drag coefficient is constant for *Re* > 3,500.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The further the drag coefficient *Cd* is, in general, a function of the orientation of the flow with respect to the object (apart from symmetrical objects like a sphere).
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] For example, a car cruising on a highway at 50 mph (80 km/h) may require only 10 horsepower (7.5 kW) to overcome aerodynamic drag, but that same car at 100 mph (160 km/h) requires 80 hp (60 kW).
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] With a doubling of speeds, the drag/force quadruples per the formula.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Exerting 4 times the force over a fixed distance produces 4 times as much work.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] At twice the speed, the work (resulting in displacement over a fixed distance) is done twice as fast.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Since power is the rate of doing work, 4 times the work done in half the time requires 8 times the power.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Where $v_{w}$ is the wind speed and $v_{o}$ is the object speed (both relative to ground).
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The hyperbolic cotangent also has a limit value of one, for large time *t*.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Velocity asymptotically tends to the terminal velocity *vt*, strictly from above *vt*.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] For objects of water-like density (raindrops, hail, live objects—mammals, birds, insects, etc.) falling in air near Earth's surface at sea level, the terminal velocity is roughly equal to $v_{t}=90{\sqrt {d}},\,$ with *d* in metres and *vt* in m/s.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Terminal velocity for very small objects (pollen, etc.) at low Reynolds numbers is determined by Stokes law.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In short, terminal velocity is higher for larger creatures, and thus potentially more deadly.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] A creature such as a mouse falling at its terminal velocity is much more likely to survive impact with the ground than a human falling at its terminal velocity.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The equation for **viscous resistance** or **linear drag** is appropriate for objects or particles moving through a fluid at relatively slow speeds (assuming there is no turbulence).
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Purely laminar flow only exists up to Re = 0.1 under this definition.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In this case, the force of drag is approximately proportional to velocity.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The velocity asymptotically approaches the terminal velocity $v_{t}={\frac {(\rho -\rho _{0})Vg}{b}}$ .
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] For a given b , denser objects fall more quickly.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] For the special case of small spherical objects moving slowly through a viscous fluid (and thus at small Reynolds number), George Gabriel Stokes derived an expression for the drag constant: $b=6\pi \eta r\,$ where r is the Stokes radius of the particle, and $\eta$ is the fluid viscosity.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] For example, consider a small sphere with radius r = 0.5 micrometre (diameter = 1.0 μm) moving through water at a velocity v of 10 μm/s.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Using 10−3 Pa·s as the dynamic viscosity of water in SI units, we find a drag force of 0.09 pN.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] This is about the drag force that a bacterium experiences as it swims through water.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] For Reynolds numbers less than 1, Stokes' law applies and the drag coefficient approaches ${\frac {24}{Re}}$ .
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In aerodynamics, **aerodynamic drag**, also known as **air resistance**, is the fluid drag force that acts on any moving solid body in the direction of the air's freestream flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Alternatively, calculated from the flow field perspective (far-field approach), the drag force results from three natural phenomena: shock waves, vortex sheet, and viscosity.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] When the airplane produces lift, another drag component results.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Induced drag, symbolized $D_{i}$ , is due to a modification of the pressure distribution due to the trailing vortex system that accompanies the lift production.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] An alternative perspective on lift and drag is gained from considering the change of momentum of the airflow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The wing intercepts the airflow and forces the flow to move downward.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] This results in an equal and opposite force acting upward on the wing which is the lift force.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The change of momentum of the airflow downward results in a reduction of the rearward momentum of the flow which is the result of a force acting forward on the airflow and applied by the wing to the air flow; an equal but opposite force acts on the wing rearward which is the induced drag.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Another drag component, namely wave drag, $D_{w}$ , results from shock waves in transonic and supersonic flight speeds.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The shock waves induce changes in the boundary layer and pressure distribution over the body surface.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Therefore, there are three ways of categorizing drag.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The pressure distribution acting on a body's surface *exerts* normal forces on the body.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Those forces can be added together and the component of that force that acts downstream represents the drag force, $D_{pr}$ .
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The nature of these normal forces combines shock wave effects, vortex system generation effects, and wake viscous mechanisms.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Viscosity of the fluid has a major effect on drag.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In the absence of viscosity, the pressure forces acting to hinder the vehicle are canceled by a pressure force further aft that acts to push the vehicle forward; this is called pressure recovery and the result is that the drag is zero.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] That is to say, the work the body does on the airflow is reversible and is recovered as there are no frictional effects to convert the flow energy into heat.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Pressure recovery acts even in the case of viscous flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Viscosity, however results in pressure drag and it is the dominant component of drag in the case of vehicles with regions of separated flow, in which the pressure recovery is infective.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The friction drag force, which is a tangential force on the aircraft surface, depends substantially on boundary layer configuration and viscosity.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The net friction drag, $D_{f}$ , is calculated as the downstream projection of the viscous forces evaluated over the body's surface.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The sum of friction drag and pressure (form) drag is called viscous drag.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] This drag component is due to viscosity.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The idea that a moving body passing through air or another fluid encounters resistance had been known since the time of Aristotle.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] According to Mervyn O'Gorman, this was named "drag" by Archibald Reith Low.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Louis Charles Breguet's paper of 1922 began efforts to reduce drag by streamlining.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Breguet went on to put his ideas into practice by designing several record-breaking aircraft in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Ludwig Prandtl's boundary layer theory in the 1920s provided the impetus to minimise skin friction.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] A further major call for streamlining was made by Sir Melvill Jones who provided the theoretical concepts to demonstrate emphatically the importance of streamlining in aircraft design.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In 1929 his paper 'The Streamline Airplane' presented to the Royal Aeronautical Society was seminal.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] He proposed an ideal aircraft that would have minimal drag which led to the concepts of a 'clean' monoplane and retractable undercarriage.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The aspect of Jones's paper that most shocked the designers of the time was his plot of the horse power required versus velocity, for an actual and an ideal plane.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] By looking at a data point for a given aircraft and extrapolating it horizontally to the ideal curve, the velocity gain for the same power can be seen.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] When Jones finished his presentation, a member of the audience described the results as being of the same level of importance as the Carnot cycle in thermodynamics.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The interaction of parasitic and induced drag *vs.* airspeed can be plotted as a characteristic curve, illustrated here.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In aviation, this is often referred to as the *power curve*, and is important to pilots because it shows that, below a certain airspeed, maintaining airspeed counterintuitively requires *more* thrust as speed decreases, rather than less.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The consequences of being "behind the curve" in flight are important and are taught as part of pilot training.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] At the subsonic airspeeds where the "U" shape of this curve is significant, wave drag has not yet become a factor, and so it is not shown in the curve.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Wave drag, sometimes referred to as compressibility drag, is drag that is created when a body moves in a compressible fluid and at the speed that is close to the speed of sound in that fluid.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In aerodynamics, wave drag consists of multiple components depending on the speed regime of the flight.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In transonic flight, wave drag is the result of the formation of shockwaves in the fluid, formed when local areas of supersonic (Mach number greater than 1.0) flow are created.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In practice, supersonic flow occurs on bodies traveling well below the speed of sound, as the local speed of air increases as it accelerates over the body to speeds above Mach 1.0.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] However, full supersonic flow over the vehicle will not develop until well past Mach 1.0.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Aircraft flying at transonic speed often incur wave drag through the normal course of operation.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In transonic flight, wave drag is commonly referred to as **transonic compressibility drag**.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Transonic compressibility drag increases significantly as the speed of flight increases towards Mach 1.0, dominating other forms of drag at those speeds.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In supersonic flight (Mach numbers greater than 1.0), **wave drag** is the result of shockwaves present in the fluid and attached to the body, typically **oblique shockwaves** formed at the leading and trailing edges of the body.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In highly supersonic flows, or in bodies with turning angles sufficiently large, **unattached shockwaves**, or **bow waves** will instead form.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Additionally, local areas of transonic flow behind the initial shockwave may occur at lower supersonic speeds, and can lead to the development of additional, smaller shockwaves present on the surfaces of other lifting bodies, similar to those found in transonic flows.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In supersonic flow regimes, **wave drag** is commonly separated into two components, **supersonic lift-dependent wave drag** and **supersonic volume-dependent wave drag**.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The closed form solution for the minimum wave drag of a body of revolution with a fixed length was found by Sears and Haack, and is known as the **Sears-Haack Distribution**.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Similarly, for a fixed volume, the shape for minimum wave drag is the **Von Karman Ogive**.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The Busemann biplane theoretical concept is not subject to wave drag when operated at its design speed, but is incapable of generating lift in this condition.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In 1752 d'Alembert proved that potential flow, the 18th century state-of-the-art inviscid flow theory amenable to mathematical solutions, resulted in the prediction of zero drag.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] This was in contradiction with experimental evidence, and became known as d'Alembert's paradox.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In the 19th century the Navier–Stokes equations for the description of viscous flow were developed by Saint-Venant, Navier, and Stokes.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Stokes derived the drag around a sphere at very low Reynolds numbers, the result of which is called Stokes' law.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] In the limit of high Reynolds numbers, the Navier–Stokes equations approach the inviscid Euler equations, of which the potential-flow solutions considered by d'Alembert are solutions.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] However, all experiments at high Reynolds numbers showed there is drag.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] Attempts to construct inviscid steady flow solutions to the Euler equations, other than the potential flow solutions, did not result in realistic results.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The notion of boundary layers—introduced by Prandtl in 1904, founded on both theory and experiments—explained the causes of drag at high Reynolds numbers.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamic-drag] The boundary layer is the thin layer of fluid close to the object's boundary, where viscous effects remain important even when the viscosity is very small (or equivalently the Reynolds number is very large).
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Modern aerodynamics only dates back to the seventeenth century, but aerodynamic forces have been harnessed by humans for thousands of years in sailboats and windmills, and images and stories of flight appear throughout recorded history including the Ancient Greek legend of Icarus and Daedalus.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Fundamental concepts of continuum, drag, and pressure gradients appear in the work of Aristotle and Archimedes.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In 1726, Sir Isaac Newton became the first person to develop a theory of air resistance, making him one of the first aerodynamicists.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Dutch-Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli followed in 1738 with *Hydrodynamica* in which he described a fundamental relationship between pressure, density, and flow velocity for incompressible flow known today as Bernoulli's principle, which provides one method for calculating aerodynamic lift.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In 1757, Leonhard Euler published the more general Euler equations which could be applied to both compressible and incompressible flows.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The Euler equations were extended to incorporate the effects of viscosity in the first half of the 1800s, resulting in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The Navier–Stokes equations are the most general governing equations of fluid flow but are difficult to solve for the flow around all but the simplest of shapes.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In 1799, Sir George Cayley became the first person to identify the four aerodynamic forces of flight (weight, lift, drag, and thrust), as well as the relationships between them, and in doing so outlined the path toward achieving heavier-than-air flight for the next century.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In 1871, Francis Herbert Wenham constructed the first wind tunnel, allowing precise measurements of aerodynamic forces.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Drag theories were developed by Jean Le Rond d'Alembert, Gustav Kirchhoff, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In 1889, Charles Renard, a French aeronautical engineer, became the first person to reasonably predict the power needed for sustained flight.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Otto Lilienthal, the first person to become highly successful with glider flights, was also the first to propose thin, curved airfoils that would produce high lift and low drag.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Building on these developments as well as research carried out in their own wind tunnel, the Wright brothers flew the first powered airplane on December 17, 1903.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] During the time of the first flights, Frederick W.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Lanchester, Martin Kutta, and Nikolai Zhukovsky independently created theories which connected circulation of a fluid flow to lift.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Kutta and Zhukovsky then developed a two-dimensional wing theory.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Expanding upon the work of Lanchester, Ludwig Prandtl is credited with developing the mathematics behind thin-airfoil and lifting-line theories as well as working with boundary layers.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] As aircraft speed increased designers began to encounter challenges associated with air compressibility at speeds near the speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The differences in airflow under such conditions lead to problems in aircraft control, increased drag due to shock waves and the threat of structural failure due to aeroelastic flutter.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The ratio of the flow speed to the speed of sound was named the Mach number after Ernst Mach who was one of the first to investigate the properties of the supersonic flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Macquorn Rankine and Pierre Henri Hugoniot independently developed the theory for flow properties before and after a shock wave, while Jakob Ackeret led the initial work of calculating the lift and drag of supersonic airfoils.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Theodore von Kármán and Hugh Latimer Dryden introduced the term transonic to describe flow speeds between the critical Mach number and Mach 1 where drag increases rapidly.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The rapid increase in drag led aerodynamicists and aviators to disagree on whether supersonic flight was achievable until the sound barrier was broken in 1947 using the Bell X-1 aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] By the time the sound barrier was broken, aerodynamicists' understanding of the subsonic and low supersonic flow had matured.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The Cold War prompted the design of an ever-evolving line of high-performance aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Computational fluid dynamics began as an effort to solve for flow properties around complex objects and has rapidly grown to the point where entire aircraft can be designed using computer software, with wind-tunnel tests followed by flight tests to confirm the computer predictions.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Understanding of supersonic and hypersonic aerodynamics has matured since the 1960s, and the goals of aerodynamicists have shifted from the behaviour of fluid flow to the engineering of a vehicle such that it interacts predictably with the fluid flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Understanding the motion of air around an object (often called a flow field) enables the calculation of forces and moments acting on the object.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In many aerodynamics problems, the forces of interest are the fundamental forces of flight: lift, drag, thrust, and weight.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Of these, lift and drag are aerodynamic forces, i.e. forces due to air flow over a solid body.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Calculation of these quantities is often founded upon the assumption that the flow field behaves as a continuum.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Continuum flow fields are characterized by properties such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, which may be functions of position and time.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] These properties may be directly or indirectly measured in aerodynamics experiments or calculated starting with the equations for conservation of mass, momentum, and energy in air flows.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Density, flow velocity, and an additional property, viscosity, are used to classify flow fields.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Flow velocity is used to classify flows according to speed regime.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are flow fields in which the air speed field is always below the local speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Transonic flows include both regions of subsonic flow and regions in which the local flow speed is greater than the local speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Supersonic flows are defined to be flows in which the flow speed is greater than the speed of sound everywhere.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] A fourth classification, hypersonic flow, refers to flows where the flow speed is much greater than the speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree on the precise definition of hypersonic flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Compressible flow accounts for varying density within the flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are often idealized as incompressible, i.e. the density is assumed to be constant.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Transonic and supersonic flows are compressible, and calculations that neglect the changes of density in these flow fields will yield inaccurate results.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Viscosity is associated with the frictional forces in a flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In some flow fields, viscous effects are very small, and approximate solutions may safely neglect viscous effects.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] These approximations are called inviscid flows.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity is not neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Finally, aerodynamic problems may also be classified by the flow environment.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] External aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes (e.g. around an airplane wing), while internal aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages inside solid objects (e.g. through a jet engine).
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Unlike liquids and solids, gases are composed of discrete molecules which occupy only a small fraction of the volume filled by the gas.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] On a molecular level, flow fields are made up of the collisions of many individual gas molecules among themselves, and their collisions with solid surfaces.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] However, in most aerodynamics applications, the discrete molecular nature of gases is ignored, and the flow field is assumed to behave as a continuum.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] This assumption allows fluid properties such as density and flow velocity to be defined everywhere within the flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The validity of the continuum assumption is dependent on the density of the gas and the application in question.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] For the continuum assumption to be valid, the mean free path length must be much smaller than the length scale of the application in question.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] For example, many aerodynamics applications deal with aircraft flying in atmospheric conditions, where the mean free path length is on the order of micrometers and where the body is orders of magnitude larger.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In these cases, the length scale of the aircraft ranges from a few meters to a few tens of meters, which is much larger than the mean free path length.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] For such applications, the continuum assumption is reasonable.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The continuum assumption is less valid for extremely low-density flows like those encountered by vehicles at very high altitudes (e.g.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] 300,000 ft/90 km) or satellites in Low Earth orbit.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In these cases, statistical mechanics is a more accurate method of solving the problem than is continuum aerodynamics.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The Knudsen number can be used to guide the choice between statistical mechanics and the continuous formulation of aerodynamics.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The assumption of a fluid continuum allows problems in aerodynamics to be solved using fluid dynamics conservation laws.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Together, the equations are known as Navier–Stokes equations, although some authors define the term to only include the momentum equation(s).
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Navier–Stokes equations have no known analytical solution and are solved in modern aerodynamics using computational techniques.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Because computational methods using high speed computers were not historically available and the high computational cost of solving these complex equations now that they are available, simplifications of the Navier–Stokes equations have been and continue to be employed.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Euler equations are a set of similar conservation equations which neglect viscosity and may be used in cases where the effect of viscosity is expected to be small.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Further simplifications lead to Laplace's equation and potential flow theory.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Additionally, Bernoulli's equation is a solution in one dimension to both the momentum and energy conservation equations.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The ideal gas law or another such equation of state is often used in conjunction with these equations to form a determined system which allows the solution for the unknown variables.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems are classified by the flow environment or properties of the flow, including flow speed, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] *External* aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Evaluating the lift and drag on an airplane or the shock waves that form in front of the nose of a rocket are examples of external aerodynamics.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] *Internal* aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages in solid objects.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] For instance, internal aerodynamics encompasses the study of the airflow through a jet engine or through an air conditioning pipe.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems can also be classified according to whether the flow speed is below, near or above the speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree over the precise definition of hypersonic flow; a rough definition considers flows with Mach numbers above 5 to be hypersonic.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The influence of viscosity on the flow dictates a third classification.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Some problems may encounter only very small viscous effects, in that case viscosity can be considered to be negligible.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The approximations to these problems are called inviscid flows.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity cannot be neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] An incompressible flow is a flow in which density is constant in both time and space.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Although all real fluids are compressible, a flow is often approximated as incompressible if the effect of the density changes cause only small changes to the calculated results.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] This is more likely to be true when the flow speeds are significantly lower than the speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Effects of compressibility are more significant at speeds close to or above the speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The Mach number is used to evaluate whether the incompressibility can be assumed, otherwise the effects of compressibility must be included.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Subsonic (or low-speed) aerodynamics describes fluid motion in flows which are much lower than the speed of sound everywhere in the flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] There are several branches of subsonic flow but one special case arises when the flow is inviscid, incompressible and irrotational.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] This case is called potential flow and allows the differential equations which describe the flow to be a simplified version of the equations of fluid dynamics, thus making available to the aerodynamicist a range of quick and easy solutions.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In solving a subsonic problem, one decision to be made by the aerodynamicist is whether to incorporate the effects of compressibility.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Compressibility is a description of the amount of change of density in the flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] When the effects of compressibility on the solution are small, the assumption that density is constant may be made.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The problem is then an incompressible low-speed aerodynamics problem.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] When the density is allowed to vary, the flow is called compressible.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In air, compressibility effects are usually ignored when the Mach number in the flow does not exceed 0.3 (about 335 feet (102 m) per second or 228 miles (366 km) per hour at 60 °F (16 °C)).
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Above Mach 0.3, the problem flow should be described using compressible aerodynamics.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] According to the theory of aerodynamics, a flow is considered to be compressible if the density changes along a streamline.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] This means that–unlike incompressible flow–changes in density are considered.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In general, this is the case where the Mach number in part or all of the flow exceeds 0.3.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The Mach 0.3 value is rather arbitrary, but it is used because gas flows with a Mach number below that value demonstrate changes in density of less than 5%.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Furthermore, that maximum 5% density change occurs at the stagnation point (the point on the object where flow speed is zero), while the density changes around the rest of the object will be significantly lower.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Transonic, supersonic, and hypersonic flows are all compressible flows.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The term Transonic refers to a range of flow velocities just below and above the local speed of sound (generally taken as Mach 0.8–1.2).
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] It is defined as the range of speeds between the critical Mach number, when some parts of the airflow over an aircraft become supersonic, and a higher speed, typically near Mach 1.2, when all of the airflow is supersonic.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Between these speeds, some of the airflow is supersonic, while some of the airflow is not supersonic.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Supersonic aerodynamic problems are those involving flow speeds greater than the speed of sound.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Calculating the lift on the Concorde during cruise can be an example of a supersonic aerodynamic problem.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Supersonic flow behaves very differently from subsonic flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Fluids react to differences in pressure; pressure changes are how a fluid is "told" to respond to its environment.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Therefore, since sound is in fact, an infinitesimal pressure difference propagating through a fluid, the speed of sound in that fluid can be considered the fastest speed that "information" can travel in the flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] This difference most obviously manifests itself in the case of a fluid striking an object.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In front of that object, the fluid builds up a stagnation pressure as impact with the object brings the moving fluid to rest.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In fluid traveling at subsonic speed, this pressure disturbance can propagate upstream, changing the flow pattern ahead of the object and giving the impression that the fluid "knows" the object is there by seemingly adjusting its movement and is flowing around it.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In a supersonic flow, however, the pressure disturbance cannot propagate upstream.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Thus, when the fluid finally reaches the object it strikes it and the fluid is forced to change its properties – temperature, density, pressure, and Mach number—in an extremely violent and irreversible fashion called a shock wave.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The presence of shock waves, along with the compressibility effects of high-flow velocity (see Reynolds number) fluids, is the central difference between the supersonic and subsonic aerodynamics regimes.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, hypersonic speeds are speeds that are highly supersonic.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In the 1970s, the term generally came to refer to speeds of Mach 5 (5 times the speed of sound) and above.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The hypersonic regime is a subset of the supersonic regime.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Hypersonic flow is characterized by high temperature flow behind a shock wave, viscous interaction, and chemical dissociation of gas.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The incompressible and compressible flow regimes produce many associated phenomena, such as boundary layers and turbulence.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The concept of a boundary layer is important in many problems in aerodynamics.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The viscosity and fluid friction in the air is approximated as being significant only in this thin layer.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] This assumption makes the description of such aerodynamics much more tractable mathematically.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, turbulence is characterized by chaotic property changes in the flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] These include low momentum diffusion, high momentum convection, and rapid variation of pressure and flow velocity in space and time.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Flow that is not turbulent is called laminar flow.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is a significant element of vehicle design, including road cars and trucks where the main goal is to reduce the vehicle drag coefficient, and racing cars, where in addition to reducing drag the goal is also to increase the overall level of downforce.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is also important in the prediction of forces and moments acting on sailing vessels.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] It is used in the design of mechanical components such as hard drive heads.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Structural engineers resort to aerodynamics, and particularly aeroelasticity, when calculating wind loads in the design of large buildings, bridges, and wind turbines.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The aerodynamics of internal passages is important in heating/ventilation, gas piping, and in automotive engines where detailed flow patterns strongly affect the performance of the engine.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Urban aerodynamics are studied by town planners and designers seeking to improve amenity in outdoor spaces, or in creating urban microclimates to reduce the effects of urban pollution.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] The field of environmental aerodynamics describes ways in which atmospheric circulation and flight mechanics affect ecosystems.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic equations are used in numerical weather prediction.
[src:aerodynamics/aerodynamics] Sports in which aerodynamics are of crucial importance include soccer, table tennis, cricket, baseball, and golf, in which most players can control the trajectory of the ball using the "Magnus effect".
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Aircraft are prone to aeroelastic effects because they need to be lightweight while enduring large aerodynamic loads.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] **flutter** which is uncontained vibration that can lead to the destruction of an aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Aeroelasticity problems can be prevented by adjusting the mass, stiffness or aerodynamics of structures which can be determined and verified through the use of calculations, *ground vibration tests* and *flight flutter trials*.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Flutter of control surfaces is usually eliminated by the careful placement of *mass balances*.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] The synthesis of aeroelasticity with thermodynamics is known as *aerothermoelasticity*, and its synthesis with control theory is known as *aeroservoelasticity*.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] The second failure of Samuel Langley's prototype plane on the Potomac was attributed to aeroelastic effects (specifically, torsional divergence).
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] An early scientific work on the subject was George Bryan's *Theory of the Stability of a Rigid Aeroplane* published in 1906.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Problems with torsional divergence plagued aircraft in the First World War and were solved largely by trial-and-error and ad hoc stiffening of the wing.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] The first recorded and documented case of flutter in an aircraft was that which occurred to a Handley Page O/400 bomber during a flight in 1916, when it suffered a violent tail oscillation, which caused extreme distortion of the rear fuselage and the elevators to move asymmetrically.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Although the aircraft landed safely, in the subsequent investigation F.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] One of his recommendations was that left and right elevators should be rigidly connected by a stiff shaft, which was to subsequently become a design requirement.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] In addition, the National Physical Laboratory (NPL) was asked to investigate the phenomenon theoretically, which was subsequently carried out by Leonard Bairstow and Arthur Fage.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] In 1926, Hans Reissner published a theory of wing divergence, leading to much further theoretical research on the subject.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] The term *aeroelasticity* itself was coined by Harold Roxbee Cox and Alfred Pugsley at the Royal Aircraft Establishment (RAE), Farnborough in the early 1930s.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] In the development of aeronautical engineering at Caltech, Theodore von Kármán started a course "Elasticity applied to Aeronautics".
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] After teaching the course for one term, Kármán passed it over to Ernest Edwin Sechler, who developed aeroelasticity in that course and in publication of textbooks on the subject.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] In 1947, Arthur Roderick Collar defined aeroelasticity as "the study of the mutual interaction that takes place within the triangle of the inertial, elastic, and aerodynamic forces acting on structural members exposed to an airstream, and the influence of this study on design".
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] In an aeroplane, two significant static aeroelastic effects may occur.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] *Divergence* is a phenomenon in which the elastic twist of the wing suddenly becomes theoretically infinite, typically causing the wing to fail.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] *Control reversal* is a phenomenon occurring only in wings with ailerons or other control surfaces, in which these control surfaces reverse their usual functionality (e.g., the rolling direction associated with a given aileron moment is reversed).
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Divergence occurs when a lifting surface deflects under aerodynamic load in a direction which further increases lift in a positive feedback loop.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] The increased lift deflects the structure further, which eventually brings the structure to the point of divergence.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Unlike flutter, which is another aeroelastic problem, instead of irregular oscillations, divergence causes the lifting surface to move in the same direction and when it comes to point of divergence the structure deforms.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Control surface reversal is the loss (or reversal) of the expected response of a control surface, due to deformation of the main lifting surface.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] For simple models (e.g. single aileron on an Euler-Bernoulli beam), control reversal speeds can be derived analytically as for torsional divergence.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Control reversal can be used to aerodynamic advantage, and forms part of the Kaman servo-flap rotor design.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Dynamic aeroelasticity studies the interactions among aerodynamic, elastic, and inertial forces.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] In water the mass ratio of the pitch inertia of the foil to that of the circumscribing cylinder of fluid is generally too low for binary flutter to occur, as shown by explicit solution of the simplest pitch and heave flutter stability determinant.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Structures exposed to aerodynamic forces—including wings and aerofoils, but also chimneys and bridges—are generally designed carefully within known parameters to avoid flutter.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Blunt shapes, such as chimneys, can give off a continuous stream of vortices known as a Kármán vortex street, which can induce structural oscillations.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Strakes are typically wrapped around chimneys to stop the formation of these vortices.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] In complex structures where both the aerodynamics and the mechanical properties of the structure are not fully understood, flutter can be discounted only through detailed testing.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Even changing the mass distribution of an aircraft or the stiffness of one component can induce flutter in an apparently unrelated aerodynamic component.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Famously, the original Tacoma Narrows Bridge was destroyed as a result of aeroelastic fluttering.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] In some cases, automatic control systems have been demonstrated to help prevent or limit flutter-related structural vibration.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Flow is highly non-linear in the transonic regime, dominated by moving shock waves.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Avoiding flutter is mission-critical for aircraft that fly through transonic Mach numbers.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] The role of shock waves was first analyzed by Holt Ashley.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] A phenomenon that impacts stability of aircraft known as "transonic dip", in which the flutter speed can get close to flight speed, was reported in May 1976 by Farmer and Hanson of the Langley Research Center.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Buffeting is a high-frequency instability, caused by airflow separation or shock wave oscillations from one object striking another.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] It is caused by a sudden impulse of load increasing.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Generally it affects the tail unit of the aircraft structure due to air flow downstream of the wing.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] In the period 1950–1970, AGARD developed the *Manual on Aeroelasticity* which details the processes used in solving and verifying aeroelastic problems along with standard examples that can be used to test numerical solutions.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Aeroelasticity involves not just the external aerodynamic loads and the way they change but also the structural, damping and mass characteristics of the aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Prediction involves making a mathematical model of the aircraft as a series of masses connected by springs and dampers which are tuned to represent the dynamic characteristics of the aircraft structure.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] The model also includes details of applied aerodynamic forces and how they vary.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] The model can be used to predict the flutter margin and, if necessary, test fixes to potential problems.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Small carefully chosen changes to mass distribution and local structural stiffness can be very effective in solving aeroelastic problems.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] Methods of predicting flutter in linear structures include the *p-method*, the *k-method* and the *p-k method*.
[src:aerodynamics/aeroelasticity] For nonlinear systems, flutter is usually interpreted as a limit cycle oscillation (LCO), and methods from the study of dynamical systems can be used to determine the speed at which flutter will occur.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] A significant part of **aeronautical science** is a branch of dynamics called aerodynamics, which deals with the motion of air and the way that it interacts with objects in motion, such as an aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Attempts to fly without any real aeronautical understanding have been made from the earliest times, typically by constructing wings and jumping from a tower with crippling or lethal results.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Wiser investigators sought to gain some rational understanding through the study of bird flight.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Medieval Islamic Golden Age scientists such as Abbas ibn Firnas also made such studies.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] The founders of modern aeronautics, Leonardo da Vinci in the Renaissance and Cayley in 1799, both began their investigations with studies of bird flight.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Man-carrying kites are believed to have been used extensively in ancient China.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] In 1282 the Italian explorer Marco Polo described the Chinese techniques then current.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] The Chinese also constructed small hot air balloons, or lanterns, and rotary-wing toys.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] An early European to provide any scientific discussion of flight was Roger Bacon, who described principles of operation for the lighter-than-air balloon and the flapping-wing ornithopter, which he envisaged would be constructed in the future.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] The lifting medium for his balloon would be an "aether" whose composition he did not know.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] In the late fifteenth century, Leonardo da Vinci followed up his study of birds with designs for some of the earliest flying machines, including the flapping-wing ornithopter and the rotating-wing helicopter.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Although his designs were rational, they were not based on particularly good science.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Many of his designs, such as a four-person screw-type helicopter, have severe flaws.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Da Vinci's work was lost after his death and did not reappear until it had been overtaken by the work of George Cayley.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] The modern era of lighter-than-air flight began early in the 17th century with Galileo's experiments in which he showed that air has weight.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Around 1650 Cyrano de Bergerac wrote some fantasy novels in which he described the principle of ascent using a substance (dew) he supposed to be lighter than air, and descending by releasing a controlled amount of the substance.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Francesco Lana de Terzi measured the pressure of air at sea level and in 1670 proposed the first scientifically credible lifting medium in the form of hollow metal spheres from which all the air had been pumped out.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] These would be lighter than the displaced air and able to lift an airship.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] His proposed methods of controlling height are still in use today; by carrying ballast which may be dropped overboard to gain height, and by venting the lifting containers to lose height.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] In practice de Terzi's spheres would have collapsed under air pressure, and further developments had to wait for more practicable lifting gases.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] From the mid-18th century the Montgolfier brothers in France began experimenting with balloons.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Their balloons were made of paper, and early experiments using steam as the lifting gas were short-lived due to its effect on the paper as it condensed.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Meanwhile, the discovery of hydrogen led Joseph Black in c.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] 1780 to propose its use as a lifting gas, though practical demonstration awaited a gas-tight balloon material.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] On hearing of the Montgolfier Brothers' invitation, the French Academy member Jacques Charles offered a similar demonstration of a hydrogen balloon.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Charles and two craftsmen, the Robert brothers, developed a gas-tight material of rubberised silk for the envelope.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] The hydrogen gas was to be generated by chemical reaction during the filling process.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] The Montgolfier designs had several shortcomings, not least the need for dry weather and a tendency for sparks from the fire to set light to the paper balloon.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] The manned design had a gallery around the base of the balloon rather than the hanging basket of the first, unmanned design, which brought the paper closer to the fire.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] On their free flight, De Rozier and d'Arlandes took buckets of water and sponges to douse these fires as they arose.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] On the other hand, the manned design of Charles was essentially modern.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] As a result of these exploits, the hot air balloon became known as the *Montgolfière* type and the gas balloon the *Charlière*.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Charles and the Robert brothers' next balloon, *La Caroline*, was a Charlière that followed Jean Baptiste Meusnier's proposals for an elongated dirigible balloon, and was notable for having an outer envelope with the gas contained in a second, inner ballonet.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] On 19 September 1784, it completed the first flight of over 100 kilometres (62 mi), between Paris and Beuvry, despite the man-powered propulsive devices proving useless.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] The balloon envelope was made of goldbeater's skin.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] The first flight ended in disaster and the approach has seldom been used since.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Sir George Cayley (1773–1857) is widely acknowledged as the founder of modern aeronautics.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] He was first called the "father of the aeroplane" in 1846 and Henson called him the "father of aerial navigation." He was the first true scientific aerial investigator to publish his work, which included for the first time the underlying principles and forces of flight.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] In 1809 he began the publication of a landmark three-part treatise titled "On Aerial Navigation" (1809–1810).
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] He developed the modern conventional form of the fixed-wing aeroplane having a stabilising tail with both horizontal and vertical surfaces, flying gliders both unmanned and manned.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] He introduced the use of the whirling arm test rig to investigate the aerodynamics of flight, using it to discover the benefits of the curved or cambered aerofoil over the flat wing he had used for his first glider.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] He also identified and described the importance of dihedral, diagonal bracing and drag reduction, and contributed to the understanding and design of ornithopters and parachutes.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Another significant invention was the tension-spoked wheel, which he devised in order to create a light, strong wheel for aircraft undercarriage.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] During the 19th century, Cayley's ideas were further developed, tested, and formalised.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Public and scientific interest in aeronautics grew during the Victorian era, with notable contributions from figures such as John Stringfellow, James Glaisher, Francis Wenham, and Frederick Brearey.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Wenham, Glaisher, and Brearey co-founded the Aeronautical Society of Great Britain in 1866, together with the 8th Duke of Argyll.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Although aeronautical research at the time remained largely experimental, the Society played an important role in promoting heavier-than-air flight, including through the First Aeronautical Exhibition held in 1868 at The Crystal Palace.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] These developments, along with growing international interest, helped lay the groundwork for the later work of Horatio Phillips among others, but more importantly of Otto Lilienthal, a German engineer and businessman who became known as the "flying man".
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] He was the first person to make well-documented, repeated, successful flights with gliders, therefore making the idea of "heavier than air" a reality.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Newspapers and magazines published photographs of Lilienthal gliding, favourably influencing public and scientific opinion about the possibility of flying machines becoming practical.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] His work led to the development of the modern wing.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] His flight attempts in Berlin in the year 1891 are seen as the beginning of human flight and the "Lilienthal Normalsegelapparat" is considered to be the first air plane in series production, making the *Maschinenfabrik Otto Lilienthal* in Berlin the first air plane production company in the world.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Otto Lilienthal is often referred to as either the "father of aviation" or "father of flight".
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Aeronautics may be divided into three main branches, Aviation, Aeronautical science and Aeronautical engineering.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Aviation is the art or practice of aeronautics.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Historically aviation meant only heavier-than-air flight, but nowadays it includes flying in balloons and airships.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Aeronautical engineering covers the design and construction of aircraft, including how they are powered, how they are used and how they are controlled for safe operation.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] A major part of aeronautical engineering is aerodynamics, the science of passing through the air.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] With the increasing activity in space flight, nowadays aeronautics and astronautics are often combined as aerospace engineering.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] The science of aerodynamics deals with the motion of air and the way that it interacts with objects in motion, such as an aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] A rocket or rocket vehicle is a missile, spacecraft, aircraft or other vehicle which obtains thrust from a rocket engine.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] In all rockets, the exhaust is formed entirely from propellants carried within the rocket before use.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Rocket engines work by action and reaction.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Rocket engines push rockets forwards simply by throwing their exhaust backwards extremely fast.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Rockets for military and recreational uses date back to at least 13th-century China.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Significant scientific, interplanetary and industrial use did not occur until the 20th century, when rocketry was the enabling technology of the Space Age, including setting foot on the Moon.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Rockets are used for fireworks, weaponry, ejection seats, launch vehicles for artificial satellites, human spaceflight and exploration of other planets.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] While comparatively inefficient for low speed use, they are very lightweight and powerful, capable of generating large accelerations and of attaining extremely high speeds with reasonable efficiency.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Chemical rockets are the most common type of rocket and they typically create their exhaust by the combustion of rocket propellant.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] Chemical rockets store a large amount of energy in an easily released form, and can be very dangerous.
[src:aerodynamics/aeronautics] However, careful design, testing, construction and use minimizes risks.
[src:aerodynamics/aerostatics] A subfield of fluid statics, **aerostatics** is the study of gases that are not in motion with respect to the coordinate system in which they are considered.
[src:aerodynamics/aerostatics] The corresponding study of gases in motion is called aerodynamics.
[src:aerodynamics/aerostatics] Aerostatics studies density allocation, especially in air.
[src:aerodynamics/aerostatics] One of the applications of this is the barometric formula.
[src:aerodynamics/aerostatics] An aerostat is a lighter than air craft, such as an airship or balloon, which uses the principles of aerostatics to float.
[src:aerodynamics/aerostatics] where $\rho$ is the mass density of the fluid, $U_{j}$ is the instantaneous velocity, P is fluid pressure, g are the external body forces acting on the fluid, and $\tau _{ij}$ is the momentum transport coefficient.
[src:aerodynamics/aerostatics] As the fluid's static nature mandates that $U_{j}=0$ , and that $\tau _{ij}=0$ , the following set of partial differential equations representing the basic equations of aerostatics is found.
[src:aerodynamics/aerostatics] which can be employed to compute the pressure distribution in gases whose thermodynamic states are given by the equation of state for ideal gases.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] There are various types of air conditioners.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In hot weather, air conditioning can prevent heat stroke, dehydration due to excessive sweating, electrolyte imbalance, kidney failure, and other issues due to hyperthermia.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] An estimated 190,000 heat-related deaths are averted annually owing to air conditioning.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Air conditioners increase productivity in hot climates, and historians rank air conditioning as a key factor that shaped postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] As of 2022, air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Air conditioners, which typically use vapor-compression refrigeration, range in size from small units used in vehicles or single rooms to massive units that can cool large buildings.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Air source heat pumps, which can be used for heating as well as cooling, are becoming increasingly common in cooler climates.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] According to the International Energy Agency (IEA) 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used globally in 2016.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The United Nations has called for the technology to be made more sustainable to mitigate climate change and for the use of alternatives, such as passive cooling, evaporative cooling, selective shading, windcatchers, and thermal insulation.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning dates back to prehistory.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Double-walled living quarters, with a gap between the two walls to encourage air flow, were found in the ancient city of Hamoukar, in modern Syria.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Ancient Egyptian buildings also used a wide variety of passive air-conditioning techniques.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] These became widespread from the Iberian Peninsula through North Africa, the Middle East, and Northern India.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Passive techniques remained widespread until the 20th century when they fell out of fashion and were replaced by powered air conditioning.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Using information from engineering studies of traditional buildings, passive techniques are being revived and modified for 21st-century architectural designs.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Air conditioners allow the building's indoor environment to remain relatively constant, largely independent of changes in external weather conditions and internal heat loads.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] They also enable deep plan buildings to be created and have allowed people to live comfortably in hotter parts of the world.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In 1558, Giambattista della Porta described a method of chilling ice to temperatures far below its freezing point by mixing it with potassium nitrate (then called "nitre") in his popular science book *Natural Magic*.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel demonstrated "Turning Summer into Winter" for James I of England, chilling part of the Great Hall of Westminster Abbey with an apparatus of troughs and vats.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In 1758, Benjamin Franklin and John Hadley, a chemistry professor at the University of Cambridge, conducted experiments applying the principle of evaporation as a means to cool an object rapidly.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Franklin and Hadley confirmed that the evaporation of highly volatile liquids (such as alcohol and ether) could be used to drive down the temperature of an object past the freezing point of water.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] They experimented with the bulb of a mercury-in-glass thermometer as their object.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] They used a bellows to speed up the evaporation.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] They lowered the temperature of the thermometer bulb down to −14 °C (7 °F) while the ambient temperature was 18 °C (64 °F).
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Franklin noted that soon after they passed the freezing point of water 0 °C (32 °F), a thin film of ice formed on the surface of the thermometer's bulb and that the ice mass was about 6 mm (1⁄4 in) thick when they stopped the experiment upon reaching −14 °C (7 °F).
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The 19th century included many developments in compression technology.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In 1820, English scientist and inventor Michael Faraday discovered that compressing and liquefying ammonia could chill air when the liquefied ammonia was allowed to evaporate.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In 1842, Florida physician John Gorrie used compressor technology to create ice, which he used to cool air for his patients in his hospital in Apalachicola, Florida.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] He hoped to eventually use his ice-making machine to regulate the temperature of buildings.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] He envisioned centralized air conditioning that could cool entire cities.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Gorrie was granted a patent in 1851, but following the death of his main backer, he was not able to realize his invention.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In 1851, James Harrison created the first mechanical ice-making machine in Geelong, Australia, and was granted a patent for an ether vapor-compression refrigeration system in 1855 that produced three tons of ice per day.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In 1860, Harrison established a second ice company.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] He later entered the debate over competing against the American advantage of ice-refrigerated beef sales to the United Kingdom.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This innovation made the systems more compact and suitable for urban environments.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] By 1896, his factory produced 'dry air cooling apparatuses' specifically designed for the cooling and dehumidification of hospitals, theaters, large public halls, and even residential rooms, several years before the widespread commercialization of modern air conditioning.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This system operated by using an electric motor-driven ammonia compressor to chill a secondary refrigerant, typically brine (salt water).
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This cold brine was circulated through pipes to a 'dry air cooling unit' (a precursor to the modern air handler), where a fan forced ambient air over the chilled coils.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This process not only lowered the temperature but also dehumidified the air by condensing moisture on the cold surfaces.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Electricity made the development of effective units possible.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Carrier built what is considered the first modern electrical air conditioning unit.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In 1902, he installed his first air-conditioning system in the Sackett-Wilhelms Lithographing & Publishing Company in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] He patented "air conditioning" in 1906, and by 1914, the first domestic (or "residential") air conditioner was installed.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] His invention controlled both the temperature and humidity, which helped maintain consistent paper dimensions and ink alignment at the printing plant.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Later, together with six other employees, Carrier formed The Carrier Air Conditioning Company of America, a business that in 2020, employed 53,000 people and was valued at $18.6 billion.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Cramer of Charlotte, North Carolina, was exploring ways to add moisture to the air in his textile mill.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Cramer coined the term "air conditioning" in a patent claim which he filed that year, where he suggested that air conditioning was analogous to "water conditioning", then a well-known process for making textiles easier to process.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] He combined moisture with ventilation to "condition" and change the air in the factories, thus controlling the humidity that is necessary in textile plants.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Willis Carrier adopted the term and incorporated it into the name of his company.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Domestic air conditioning soon took off.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In 1914, the first domestic air conditioning was installed in Minneapolis in the home of Charles Gilbert Gates.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] It is, however, possible that the considerable device (c.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Sherman developed what would become the most common type of individual room air conditioner: one designed to sit on a window ledge.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The units went on sale in 1932 at US$10,000 to $50,000 (the equivalent of $200,000 to $1,200,000 in 2025.) A year later, the first air conditioning systems for cars were offered for sale.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Chrysler Motors introduced the first practical semi-portable air conditioning unit in 1935, and Packard became the first automobile manufacturer to offer an air conditioning unit in its cars in 1939.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Innovations in the latter half of the 20th century allowed more ubiquitous air conditioner use.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In 1945, Robert Sherman of Lynn, Massachusetts, invented a portable, in-window air conditioner that cooled, heated, humidified, dehumidified, and filtered the air.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The first inverter air conditioners were released in 1980–1981.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In 1954, Ned Cole, a 1939 architecture graduate from the University of Texas at Austin, developed the first experimental "suburb" with inbuilt air conditioning in each house.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In addition, researchers from UT's Health Service and Psychology Department studied the effects on the "artificially cooled humans." One of the more amusing discoveries was that each family reported being troubled with scorpions, the leading theory being that scorpions sought cool, shady places.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Other reported changes in lifestyle were that mothers baked more, families ate heavier foods, and they were more apt to choose hot drinks.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Air conditioner adoption tends to increase above around $10,000 (circa 2021) annual household income in warmer areas.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Global GDP growth explains around 85% of increased air condition adoption by 2050, while the remaining 15% can be explained by climate change.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The urban heat island effect was first scientifically noted by Luke Howard in the 1810s, who described London being several degrees warmer than its rural surroundings at night.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The phenomenon gained attention in the late 1960s, mainly in Japan and North America.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] From the late 1980s to early 2010s, studies began to link air conditioners to the urban heat island effect.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The phenomenon was observed in various cities such as Tokyo and Houston.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] As of 2016, an estimated 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used worldwide, with over half of them in China and the United States, and with a total cooling capacity of 11,675 gigawatts.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The International Energy Agency predicted in 2018 that the number of air conditioning units would grow to around 4 billion units by 2050 and that the total cooling capacity would grow to around 23,000 GW, with the biggest increases in India and China.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Between 1995 and 2004, the proportion of urban households in China with air conditioners increased from 8% to 70%.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Between 2010 and 2023, air conditioner use in India tripled to 24 units per 100 households, with the most ownership in Haryana, Chandigarh, Rajasthan, and Delhi and the least in Meghalaya, Tripura, Manipur, and Himachal Pradesh.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] As of 2015, nearly 100 million homes in the United States, or about 87% of US households, had air conditioning systems.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In 2019, it was estimated that 90% of new single-family homes constructed in the US included air conditioning, ranging from 99% in the South to 62% in the West.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] As of 2025, roughly half of homes in Italy, 40 percent of homes in Spain, and 20 to 25 percent of homes in France had air conditioning.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Cooling in traditional air conditioner systems is accomplished using the vapor-compression cycle, which uses a refrigerant's forced circulation and phase change between gas and liquid to transfer heat.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The vapor-compression cycle can occur within a unitary, or packaged piece of equipment, or within a chiller that is connected to terminal cooling equipment (such as a fan coil unit in an air handler) on its evaporator side and heat rejection equipment such as a cooling tower on its condenser side.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] An air source heat pump shares many components with an air conditioning system, but includes a reversing valve, which allows the unit to be used to heat as well as cool a space.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning equipment will reduce the absolute humidity of the air processed by the system if the surface of the evaporator coil is significantly cooler than the dew point of the surrounding air.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] An air conditioner designed for an occupied space will typically achieve a 30% to 60% relative humidity in the occupied space.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Most modern air-conditioning systems feature a dehumidification mode, in which the compressor runs.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] At the same time, the fan is slowed to reduce the evaporator temperature and condense more water.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Free cooling can sometimes be selected when the external air is cooler than the internal air.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In this case, the compressor does not need to be used, resulting in high cooling efficiencies for these times.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This may also be combined with seasonal thermal energy storage.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Some air conditioning systems can reverse the refrigeration cycle and act as an air source heat pump, thus heating instead of cooling the indoor environment.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] They are also commonly referred to as "reverse cycle air conditioners".
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The heat pump is significantly more energy-efficient than electric resistance heating, because it moves energy from air or groundwater to the heated space and the heat from purchased electrical energy.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] When the heat pump is in heating mode, the indoor evaporator coil switches roles and becomes the condenser coil, producing heat and the outdoor condenser unit also switches roles to serve as the evaporator and discharges cold air (colder than the ambient outdoor air).
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Most air source heat pumps become less efficient in outdoor temperatures lower than 4 °C or 40 °F.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This is partly because ice forms on the outdoor unit's heat exchanger coil, which blocks air flow over the coil.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] To compensate for this, the heat pump system must temporarily switch back into the regular air conditioning mode to switch the outdoor evaporator coil back to being the condenser coil, so it can heat up and defrost.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Therefore, some heat pump systems will have electric resistance heating in the indoor air path that is activated only in this mode to compensate for the temporary indoor air cooling, which would otherwise be uncomfortable in the winter.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Newer models have improved cold-weather performance, with efficient heating capacity down to −14 °F (−26 °C).
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] However, there is always a chance that the humidity that condenses on the heat exchanger of the outdoor unit could freeze, even in models that have improved cold-weather performance, requiring a defrosting cycle to be performed.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In this case, the heat pump is used efficiently during milder temperatures, and the system is switched to the conventional heat source when the outdoor temperature is lower.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The coefficient of performance (COP) of an air conditioning system is a ratio of useful heating or cooling provided to the work required.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Higher COPs equate to lower operating costs.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The COP usually exceeds 1; however, the exact value is highly dependent on operating conditions, especially absolute temperature and relative temperature between sink and system, and is often graphed or averaged against expected conditions.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Air conditioner equipment power in the U.S. is often described in terms of "tons of refrigeration", with each approximately equal to the cooling power of one short ton (2,000 pounds (910 kg) of ice melting in a 24-hour period.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The value is equal to 12,000 BTUIT per hour, or 3,517 watts.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Residential central air systems are usually from 1 to 5 tons (3.5 to 18 kW) in capacity.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The efficiency of air conditioners is often rated by the seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER), which is defined by the Air Conditioning, Heating and Refrigeration Institute in its 2008 standard AHRI 210/240, *Performance Rating of Unitary Air-Conditioning and Air-Source Heat Pump Equipment*.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] A similar standard is the European seasonal energy efficiency ratio (ESEER).
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Efficiency is strongly affected by the humidity of the air to be cooled.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Dehumidifying the air before attempting to cool it can reduce subsequent cooling costs by as much as 90 percent.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Thus, reducing dehumidifying costs can materially affect overall air conditioning costs.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This type of controller uses an infrared LED to relay commands from a remote control to the air conditioner.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The output of the infrared LED (like that of any infrared remote) is invisible to the human eye because its wavelength is beyond the range of visible light (940 nm).
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This system is commonly used on mini-split air conditioners because it is simple and portable.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Some window and ducted central air conditioners uses it as well.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] A wired controller, also called a "wired thermostat," is a device that controls an air conditioner by switching heating or cooling on or off.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] It uses different sensors to measure temperatures and actuate control operations.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Mechanical thermostats commonly use bimetallic strips, converting a temperature change into mechanical displacement, to actuate control of the air conditioner.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Electronic thermostats, instead, use a thermistor or other semiconductor sensor, processing temperature change as electronic signals to control the air conditioner.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] These controllers are usually used in apartments, hospitals, offices and hotel rooms, because they are permanently installed into a wall and hard-wired directly into the air conditioner unit, eliminating the need for batteries.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Ductless systems (often mini-split, though there are now ducted mini-split) typically supply conditioned and heated air to a single or a few rooms of a building, without ducts and in a decentralized manner.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Multi-zone or multi-split systems are a common application of ductless systems and allow up to eight rooms (zones or locations) to be conditioned independently from each other, each with its indoor unit and simultaneously from a single outdoor unit.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The first mini-split system was sold in 1961 by Toshiba in Japan, and the first wall-mounted mini-split air conditioner was sold in 1968 in Japan by Mitsubishi Electric, where small home sizes motivated their development.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The Mitsubishi model was the first air conditioner with a cross-flow fan.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In 1969, the first mini-split air conditioner was sold in the US.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Multi-zone ductless systems were invented by Daikin in 1973, and variable refrigerant flow systems (which can be thought of as larger multi-split systems) were also invented by Daikin in 1982.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The outdoor and indoor units can be spread across the building.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Variable refrigerant flow indoor units can also be turned off individually in unused spaces.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The lower start-up power of VRF's DC inverter compressors and their inherent DC power requirements also allow VRF solar-powered heat pumps to be run using DC-providing solar panels.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Split-system central air conditioners consist of two heat exchangers, an outside unit (the condenser) from which heat is rejected to the environment and an internal heat exchanger (the evaporator, or Fan Coil Unit, FCU) with the piped refrigerant being circulated between the two.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The FCU is then connected to the spaces to be cooled by ventilation ducts.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Floor standing air conditioners are similar to this type of air conditioner but sit within spaces that need cooling.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The chilled water is cooled by chillers in the plant, which uses a refrigeration cycle to cool water, often transferring its heat to the atmosphere even in liquid-cooled chillers through the use of cooling towers.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] A portable system has an indoor unit on wheels connected to an outdoor unit via flexible pipes, similar to a permanently fixed installed unit (such as a ductless split air conditioner).
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Hose systems, which can be *monoblock* or *air-to-air*, are vented to the outside via air ducts.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The *monoblock* type collects the water in a bucket or tray and stops when full.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The *air-to-air* type re-evaporates the water, discharges it through the ducted hose, and can run continuously.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Many but not all portable units draw indoor air and expel it outdoors through a single duct, negatively impacting their overall cooling efficiency.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Many portable air conditioners come with heat as well as a dehumidification function.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The packaged terminal air conditioner (PTAC), through-the-wall, and window air conditioners are similar.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] These units are installed on a window frame or on a wall opening.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The unit usually has an internal partition separating its indoor and outdoor sides, which contain the unit's condenser and evaporator, respectively.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] PTAC systems may be adapted to provide heating in cold weather, either directly by using an electric strip, gas, or other heaters, or by reversing the refrigerant flow to heat the interior and draw heat from the exterior air, converting the air conditioner into a heat pump.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] They may be installed in a wall opening with the help of a special sleeve on the wall and a custom grill that is flush with the wall and window air conditioners can also be installed in a window, but without a custom grill.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Packaged air conditioners (also known as self-contained units) are central systems that integrate into a single housing all the components of a split central system, and deliver air, possibly through ducts, to the spaces to be cooled.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Depending on their construction the units may be kept outdoors or indoors; draw the air to be conditioned from inside or outside a building and be water or air-cooled.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Often, outdoor units are air-cooled while indoor units are liquid-cooled using a cooling tower.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This compressor consists of a crankcase, crankshaft, piston rod, piston, piston ring, cylinder head and valves.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This compressor uses two interleaving scrolls to compress the refrigerant. it consists of one fixed and one orbiting scrolls.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This type of compressor is more efficient because it has 70 percent less moving parts than a reciprocating compressor.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This compressor use two very closely meshing spiral rotors to compress the gas.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The gas enters at the suction side and moves through the threads as the screws rotate.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The meshing rotors force the gas through the compressor, and the gas exits at the end of the screws.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The working area is the inter-lobe volume between the male and female rotors.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] It is larger at the intake end, and decreases along the length of the rotors until the exhaust port.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This change in volume is the compression.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] There are several ways to modulate the cooling capacity in refrigeration or air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The most common in air conditioning are: on-off cycling, hot gas bypass, use or not of liquid injection, manifold configurations of multiple compressors, mechanical modulation (also called digital), and inverter technology.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Hot gas bypass involves injecting a quantity of gas from discharge to the suction side.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The compressor will keep operating at the same speed, but due to the bypass, the refrigerant mass flow circulating with the system is reduced, and thus the cooling capacity is also reduced.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This naturally causes the compressor to run uselessly during the periods when the bypass is operating.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity varies between 0 and 100%.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Several compressors can be installed in the system to provide the peak cooling capacity.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Each compressor can run or not in order to stage the cooling capacity of the unit.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity is either 0/33/66 or 100% for a trio configuration and either 0/50 or 100% for a tandem.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This internal mechanical capacity modulation is based on periodic compression process with a control valve, the two scroll set move apart stopping the compression for a given time period.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This method varies refrigerant flow by changing the average time of compression, but not the actual speed of the motor.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Despite an excellent turndown ratio – from 10 to 100% of the cooling capacity, mechanically modulated scrolls have high energy consumption as the motor continuously runs.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This system uses a variable-frequency drive (also called an Inverter) to control the speed of the compressor.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The refrigerant flow rate is changed by the change in the speed of the compressor.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The turn down ratio depends on the system configuration and manufacturer.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] It modulates from 15 or 25% up to 100% at full capacity with a single inverter from 12 to 100% with a hybrid tandem.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This method is the most efficient way to modulate an air conditioner's capacity.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] It is up to 58% more efficient than a fixed speed system.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Heat waves are the most lethal type of weather phenomenon in the United States.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] A 2020 study found that areas with lower use of air conditioning correlated with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The August 2003 France heatwave resulted in approximately 15,000 deaths, where 80% of the victims were over 75 years old.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In response, the French government required all retirement homes to have at least one air-conditioned room at 25 °C (77 °F) per floor during heatwaves.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] A 2021 report estimated that around 345,000 people aged 65 and older died in 2019 from the heat, which is preventable with air conditioning.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning (including filtration, humidification, cooling and disinfection) can be used to provide a clean, safe, hypoallergenic atmosphere in hospital operating rooms and other environments where proper atmosphere is critical to patient safety and well-being.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] It is sometimes recommended for home use by people with allergies, especially mold.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] However, poorly maintained water cooling towers can promote the growth and spread of microorganisms such as *Legionella pneumophila*, the infectious agent responsible for Legionnaires' disease.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] As long as the cooling tower is kept clean (usually by means of a chlorine treatment), these health hazards can be avoided or reduced.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The state of New York has codified requirements for registration, maintenance, and testing of cooling towers to protect against Legionella.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] First designed to benefit targeted industries such as the press as well as large factories, the invention quickly spread to public agencies and administrations with studies with claims of increased productivity close to 24% in places equipped with air conditioning.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning contributed to the economic development of the American South after the 1950s by enabling industrial activities in hot climates and supporting the expansion of white-collar work in cooled office spaces.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] It also influenced urban sprawl and commuting patterns, as air-conditioned vehicles made suburban development more viable.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Historians rank air conditioning among key factors shaping postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning caused various shifts in demography, notably that of the United States starting from the 1970s.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In the US, the birth rate was lower in the spring than during other seasons until the 1970s but this difference then declined since then.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] As of 2007, the Sun Belt contained 30% of the total US population while it was inhabited by 24% of Americans at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Moreover, the summer mortality rate in the US, which had been higher in regions subject to a heat wave during the summer, also evened out.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The spread of the use of air conditioning acts as a main driver for the growth of global demand of electricity.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] A 2020 survey found that an estimated 88% of all US households use AC, increasing to 93% when solely looking at homes built between 2010 and 2020.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity in 2022, and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] There is some push to increase the energy efficiency of air conditioners.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) and the IEA found that if air conditioners could be twice as effective as now, 460 billion tons of GHG could be cut over 40 years.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The UNEP and IEA also recommended legislation to decrease the use of hydrofluorocarbons, better building insulation, and more sustainable temperature-controlled food supply chains going forward.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Refrigerants have also caused and continue to cause serious environmental issues, including ozone depletion and climate change, as several countries have not yet ratified the Kigali Amendment to reduce the consumption and production of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] CFCs and HCFCs refrigerants such as R-12 and R-22, respectively, used within air conditioners have caused damage to the ozone layer, and hydrofluorocarbon refrigerants such as R-410A and R-404A, which were designed to replace CFCs and HCFCs, are instead exacerbating climate change.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Both issues happen due to the venting of refrigerant to the atmosphere, such as during repairs.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] HFO refrigerants, used in some if not most new equipment, solve both issues with an ozone damage potential (ODP) of zero and a much lower global warming potential (GWP) in the single or double digits vs. the three or four digits of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Hydrofluorocarbons would have raised global temperatures by around 0.3–0.5 °C (0.5–0.9 °F) by 2100 without the Kigali Amendment.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] With the Kigali Amendment, the increase of global temperatures by 2100 due to hydrofluorocarbons is predicted to be around 0.06 °C (0.1 °F).
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning units also contribute to pollution as they are difficult to disassemble or repair.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Separating metal and plastic at the end of a unit's life cycle is also costly and not practical, meaning units are frequently disposed of.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Several journalists say it is an *air conditioning paradox* that arises from the usage of air conditioners to adapt to the effects of climate change, leading to higher energy consumption and heat generation as a byproduct, thereby exacerbating the problem.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Alternatives are currently being explored by governments and researchers, such as more energy-efficient systems, passive cooling techniques, and the development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] However, balancing the demand for cooling with the need to reduce carbon footprints remains a complex and pressing issue.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] As renewable energy becomes cheaper and more popular, the energy source of air conditioners is shifting towards more renewable energy sources.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The danger of high-GWP refrigerants, such as HFCs, escaping into the atmosphere and trapping heat can be mitigated through development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Socioeconomic groups with an annual household income below around $10,000 (circa 2021) tend to have a low rate of air conditioning adoption, which worsens heat-related mortality.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The lack of cooling can be hazardous, as areas with lower use of air conditioning correlate with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Premature mortality in New York City is projected to grow by between 47% and 95% in 30 years, with lower-income and vulnerable populations most at risk.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Studies on the correlation between heat-related mortality and hospitalizations and living in low socioeconomic locations can be traced in Phoenix, Arizona; Hong Kong; China; Japan; and Italy.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Costs of health care can act as another barrier: the lack of private health insurance during a 2009 heat wave in Australia was associated with heat-related hospitalization.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] A study examining the US cities of Chicago, Detroit, Minneapolis, and Pittsburgh found that black households were half as likely to have central air conditioning units when compared to their white counterparts.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Especially in cities, redlining and other historical practices mean that racial disparities are also played out in heat islands, increasing temperatures in certain parts of the city.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This is due to heat-absorbing building materials and pavements and lack of vegetation and shade coverage.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] There have been initiatives that provide cooling solutions to low-income communities, such as public cooling spaces.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Cooling has allowed for growth of indoor home space and has encouraged people, including children, to stay indoors more often.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] It has also created uniformity of different geographical areas and climate zones.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Alternatives to continual air conditioning include passive cooling, passive solar cooling, natural ventilation, operating shades to reduce solar gain, using trees, architectural shades, windows (and using window coatings) to reduce solar gain.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Buildings designed with passive air conditioning are generally less expensive to construct and maintain than buildings with conventional HVAC systems with lower energy demands.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] While tens of air changes per hour, and cooling of tens of degrees, can be achieved with passive methods, site-specific microclimate must be taken into account, complicating building design.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Many techniques can be used to increase comfort and reduce the temperature in buildings.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] These include evaporative cooling, selective shading, wind, thermal convection, and heat storage.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Passive ventilation is the process of supplying air to and removing air from an indoor space without using mechanical systems.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] It refers to the flow of external air to an indoor space as a result of pressure differences arising from natural forces.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] There are two types of natural ventilation occurring in buildings: *wind driven ventilation* and *buoyancy-driven ventilation*.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Wind driven ventilation arises from the different pressures created by wind around a building or structure, and openings being formed on the perimeter which then permit flow through the building.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Buoyancy-driven ventilation occurs as a result of the directional buoyancy force that results from temperature differences between the interior and exterior.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Since the internal heat gains which create temperature differences between the interior and exterior are created by natural processes, including the heat from people, and wind effects are variable, naturally ventilated buildings are sometimes called "breathing buildings".
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Natural solutions do not require energy for cooling purposes, and are therefore a very attractive solution.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Many ways to achieve this have been explored.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The structure of a building can help dissipate heat.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] For example, in Zimbabwe, Eastgate Development cut its energy use by 90% by utilizing termite mound inspired structures.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Coverage of windows can help reduce internal heat gain from sunlight.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Department of Energy estimates that window awnings can lower internal heat gain from sunlight by up to 77%.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The coating of roofs have also seen great success.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In the United States, painting roofs white has been shown to lower roof temperatures by as much as 30 °C.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Meanwhile, in China, a project involving the installation of green roofs — roofs covered with vegetation — not only reduced the cooling demands of buildings, but also lowered the average land surface temperature in the area by 0.91 °C.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Planting trees can also help mitigate the heat island effect.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] A study in Europe discovered that tree cover can reduce land surface temperatures in cities by as much as 12 °C during the summer.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In the United States, another study found that when tree cover reaches 40%, ground-level temperatures were lowered by nearly 6 °C.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is a building design approach that focuses on heat gain control and heat dissipation in a building in order to improve the indoor thermal comfort with low or no energy consumption.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This approach works either by preventing heat from entering the interior (heat gain prevention) or by removing heat from the building (natural cooling).
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Natural cooling utilizes on-site energy, available from the natural environment, combined with the architectural design of building components (e.g. building envelope), rather than mechanical systems to dissipate heat.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Therefore, natural cooling depends not only on the architectural design of the building but on how the site's natural resources are used as heat sinks (i.e. everything that absorbs or dissipates heat).
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Examples of on-site heat sinks are the upper atmosphere (night sky), the outdoor air (wind), and the earth/soil.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is an important tool for design of buildings for climate change adaptation – reducing dependency on energy-intensive air conditioning in warming environments.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Passive daytime radiative cooling (PDRC) surfaces reflect incoming solar radiation and heat back into outer space through the infrared window for cooling during the daytime.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Daytime radiative cooling became possible with the ability to suppress solar heating using photonic structures, which emerged through a study by Raman et al.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] PDRCs can come in a variety of forms, including paint coatings and films, that are designed to be high in solar reflectance and thermal emittance.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] PDRC applications on building roofs and envelopes have demonstrated significant decreases in energy consumption and costs.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In suburban single-family residential areas, PDRC application on roofs can potentially lower energy costs by 26% to 46%.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] PDRCs are predicted to show a market size of ~$27 billion for indoor space cooling by 2025 and have undergone a surge in research and development since the 2010s.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Hand fans have existed since prehistory.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Large human-powered fans built into buildings include the punkah.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] The Chinese inventor Ding Huan (1st century CE) of the Han dynasty invented a rotary fan for air conditioning, with seven wheels 3 m (10 ft) in diameter and manually powered by prisoners.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] 712–762) of the Tang dynasty (618–907) had the Cool Hall (*Liang Dian* 涼殿) built in the imperial palace, which the *Tang Yulin* describes as having water-powered fan wheels for air conditioning as well as rising jet streams of water from fountains.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] During the subsequent Song dynasty (960–1279), written sources mentioned the air conditioning rotary fan as even more widely used.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In areas that are cold at night or in winter, heat storage is used.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Heat may be stored in earth or masonry; air is drawn past the masonry to heat or cool it.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In areas that are below freezing at night in winter, snow and ice can be collected and stored in ice houses for later use in cooling.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This technique is over 3,700 years old in the Middle East.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Harvesting outdoor ice during winter and transporting and storing for use in summer was practiced by wealthy Europeans in the early 1600s, and became popular in Europe and the Americas towards the end of the 1600s.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] This practice was replaced by mechanical compression-cycle icemakers.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In dry, hot climates, the evaporative cooling effect may be used by placing water at the air intake, such that the draft draws air over water and then into the house.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] For this reason, it is sometimes said that the fountain, in the architecture of hot, arid climates, is like the fireplace in the architecture of cold climates.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Evaporative cooling also makes the air more humid, which can be beneficial in a dry desert climate.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] Evaporative coolers tend to feel as if they are not working during times of high humidity, when there is not much dry air with which the coolers can work to make the air as cool as possible for dwelling occupants.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] There is a longstanding political controversy about air conditioning.
[src:aerodynamics/air-conditioning] In the nations of Europe where the technology is relatively unadopted, the strongest opposition generally originates from environmentalists, European federalists, and left-wing parties, while supporters tend to be from the political right.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] An **aircraft** is a vehicle that can fly by gaining support from the air.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] It counters the force of gravity by using either static lift or the dynamic lift of an airfoil, or, in a few cases, direct downward thrust from its engines.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Common examples of aircraft include airplanes, drones, rotorcraft (including helicopters), airships (including blimps), gliders, paramotors, and hot air balloons.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Part 1 (Definitions and Abbreviations) of Subchapter A of Chapter I of Title 14 of the U.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Code of Federal Regulations states that *aircraft* "means a device that is used or intended to be used for flight in the air".
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The human activity that surrounds aircraft is called *aviation*.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The science of aviation includes the designing and building of aircraft, which is called *aeronautics*. a *crewed* aircraft is flown by an onboard pilot, whereas an unmanned aerial vehicle may be remotely controlled or *autonomous*, controlled by onboard computers.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Aircraft may be classified by different criteria, such as lift type, propulsion (if any), usage and others.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The history of aviation spans over two millennia, from the earliest innovations like kites and attempts at tower jumping to supersonic and hypersonic flight in powered, heavier-than-air jet aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Kite flying in China, dating back several hundred years BC, is considered the earliest example of man-made flight.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] In the 15th century, Leonardo da Vinci created flying machine designs incorporating aeronautical concepts, but they were unworkable due to the limitations of contemporary knowledge.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] In the late 18th century, the Montgolfier brothers invented the hot-air balloon which soon led to manned flights.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] At almost the same time, the discovery of hydrogen gas led to the invention of the hydrogen balloon.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Various theories in mechanics by physicists during the same period, such as fluid dynamics and Newton's laws of motion, led to the development of modern aerodynamics; most notably by Sir George Cayley.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Balloons, both free-flying and tethered, began to be used for military purposes from the end of the 18th century, with France establishing balloon companies during the French Revolution.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] In the 19th century, especially the second half, experiments with gliders provided the basis for learning the dynamics of winged aircraft; most notably by Cayley, Otto Lilienthal, and Octave Chanute.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] By the early 20th century, advances in engine technology and aerodynamics made controlled, powered, manned heavier-than-air flight possible for the first time.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] In 1903, following their pioneering research and experiments with wing design and aircraft control, the Wright brothers successfully incorporated all of the required elements to create and fly the first airplane.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] In 1906 Charles Frederick Page was granted the first U.S. patent for an aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The basic configuration with its characteristic cruciform tail was established by 1909, followed by rapid design and performance improvements aided by the development of more powerful engines.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The first vessels of the air were the rigid steerable balloons pioneered by Ferdinand von Zeppelin that became synonymous with airships and dominated long-distance flight until the 1930s, when large flying boats became popular for trans-oceanic routes.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] After World War II, the flying boats were in turn replaced by airplanes operating from land, made far more capable first by improved propeller engines, then by jet engines, which revolutionized both civilian air travel and military aviation.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] In the latter half of the 20th century, the development of digital electronics led to major advances in flight instrumentation and "fly-by-wire" systems.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The 21st century has seen the widespread use of pilotless drones for military, commercial, and recreational purposes.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] With computerized controls, inherently unstable aircraft designs, such as flying wings, have also become practical.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Lighter-than-air aircraft or *aerostats* use buoyancy to float in the air in much the same way that ships float on the water.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] They are characterized by one or more large cells or canopies, filled with a lifting gas such as helium, hydrogen or hot air, which is less dense than the surrounding air.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Other gases lighter than air also theoretically work; however, such gases also need to be safe for human use (non-flammable, non-toxic).
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Small hot-air balloons, called sky lanterns, were first invented in ancient China prior to the 3rd century BC and used primarily in cultural celebrations, although they also had military purposes.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] They, along with kites, were two forms of unmanned aircraft that originated from China.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Kites were also used in the military, but unlike sky lanterns, their flight is caused by the differences in air pressure beneath and above the kite.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] A balloon was originally any aerostat, while the term airship was used for large, powered aircraft designs—usually fixed-wing.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] In 1919, Frederick Handley Page was reported as referring to "ships of the air," with smaller passenger types as "Air yachts." In the 1930s, large intercontinental flying boats were also sometimes referred to as "ships of the air" or "flying-ships".
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Lighter-than-air aircraft don't typically require a pilot's license in the United States.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] In most countries in Europe, standards for flying Lighter-than-air aircraft tend to be stricter compared to the United States.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Heavier-than-air aircraft or *aerodynes* are denser than air and thus must find some way to obtain enough lift that can overcome the aircraft's weight.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] There are two ways to produce dynamic upthrust—aerodynamic lift by having air flowing past an aerofoil (such dynamic interaction of aerofoils with air is the origin of the term "aerodyne"), or powered lift in the form of reactional lift from downward engine thrust.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Aerodynamic lift involving wings is the most common, and can be achieved via two methods.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Fixed-wing aircraft (airplanes and gliders) achieve airflow past the wings by having the entire aircraft moving forward through the air, while rotorcraft (helicopters and autogyros) do so by having mobile, elongated wings spinning rapidly around a mast in an assembly known as the rotor.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Gliders were one of the first forms of a fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] They are a special type of aircraft that doesn't require an engine.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The first person to successfully build a human-carrying glider was George Cayley, who also was the first to discover the four major aerodynamic forces.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The first powered aircraft (Airplane) was invented by Wilbur and Orville Wright.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] A *rotary-wing aircraft*, *rotorwing aircraft* or *rotorcraft* is a heavier-than-air aircraft with rotary wings that spin around a vertical mast to generate lift.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The assembly of several rotor blades mounted on a single mast is referred to as a rotor.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) defines a rotorcraft as "supported in flight by the reactions of the air on one or more rotors".
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Rotorcraft generally include aircraft where one or more rotors provide lift throughout the entire flight, such as helicopters, gyroplanes, autogyros, and gyrodynes.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Compound rotorcraft augment the rotor with additional thrust engines, propellers, or static lifting surfaces.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Some types, such as helicopters, are capable of vertical takeoff and landing.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] An aircraft that uses rotor lift for vertical flight but changes to solely fixed-wing lift in horizontal flight is not a rotorcraft but a convertiplane.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The largest aircraft by weight and largest regular fixed-wing aircraft ever built, as of 2016, was the Antonov An-225 *Mriya*.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] That Soviet-built (Ukrainian SSR) six-engine transport of the 1980s was 84 m (276 ft) long, with an 88 m (289 ft) wingspan.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] It holds the world payload record, after transporting 428,834 lb (194,516 kg) of goods, and has flown 100 t (220,000 lb) loads commercially.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] With a maximum loaded weight of 550–700 t (1,210,000–1,540,000 lb), it was also the heaviest aircraft built to date.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The aircraft was destroyed during the Russo-Ukrainian War.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The largest military airplanes are the Ukrainian Antonov An-124 *Ruslan* (world's second-largest airplane, also used as a civilian transport), and American Lockheed C-5 Galaxy transport, weighing, loaded, over 380 t (840,000 lb).
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The fastest recorded powered aircraft flight and fastest recorded aircraft flight of an air-breathing powered aircraft was of the NASA X-43A *Pegasus*, a scramjet-powered, hypersonic, lifting body experimental research aircraft, at Mach 9.68 or 6,755 mph (10,870 km/h) on 16 November 2004.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Before the X-43A, the fastest recorded powered airplane flight, and still the record for the fastest manned powered airplane, was the North American X-15, rocket-powered airplane at Mach 6.7 or 7,274 km/h (4,520 mph) on 3 October 1967.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The fastest manned, air-breathing powered airplane is the Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird, a U.S. reconnaissance jet fixed-wing aircraft, having reached 3,530 km/h (2,193 mph) on 28 July 1976.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The main feature of unpowered aircraft is the inability to directly provide thrust through its engines.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] This means that all unpowered aircraft rely on the environment for sustained flight.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Gliders, for example, take advantage of their aerodynamic properties to enable them to travel long distances.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Techniques such as thermal circling, where gliders fly into warm air which allows them to rise, prolong flight time.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Due to the lack of an engine, initial propulsion assistance is usually necessary to ensure flight.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] A common glider launching method is aerotowing, where another aircraft tows the glider to an altitude from which sustained flight is possible.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Steering for a glider is also rudimentary, while more complex gliders like sailplanes usually have joysticks for steering, more basic aircraft like hang gliders rely on the pilot's physical coordination to change the centre of gravity.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] A powered aircraft is an aircraft with a source of mechanical power, used to produce thrust.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Such sources are generally engines, as is the case with airplanes, but can be human-powered in more extreme cases.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Propeller aircraft, as their name suggests, rely on propellers to produce thrust for the airplane.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Compared to engines using propellers, jet engines can provide much higher thrust, higher speeds and, above about 40,000 ft (12,000 m), greater efficiency.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Although some rotorcraft, such as rotor kites, can be unpowered, most rotorcraft are powered by either piston engines or turboprops.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Some rotorcraft, including autogyros and gyrodynes, are propelled by a conventional propeller or jet engine, with the rotor unpowered, but most modern rotorcraft have a powered rotor, allowing them to hover in place.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Autogyros and gyrodynes are steered using a rudder, similarly to propeller and jet aircraft, and rotorcraft with powered rotors, such as helicopters, turn by adjusting the pitch of the rotor cyclically, so that the rotors on one side produce more lift than the other.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Rotorcraft with powered rotors typically need a tail rotor to counter the rotational torque produced by the rotor, which can cause the helicopter to spin.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] An *aerostat* or *lighter-than-air aircraft* relies on buoyancy to maintain flight.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Aerostats include unpowered balloons (free-flying or tethered) and powered airships.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The relative density of an aerostat as a whole is lower than that of the surrounding atmospheric air (hence the name "lighter-than-air").
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Its main component is one or more gas capsules made of lightweight skins, containing a lifting gas (hot air, or any gas with lower density than air, typically hydrogen or helium) that displaces a large volume of air to generate enough buoyancy to overcome its own weight.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Payload (passengers and cargo) can then be carried on attached components such as a basket, a gondola, a cabin or various hardpoints.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] With airships, which need to be able to fly against wind, the lifting gas capsules are often protected by a more rigid outer envelope or an airframe, with other gasbags such as ballonets to help modulate buoyancy.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Aerostats are so named because they use aerostatic buoyant force that does not require any forward movement through the surrounding air mass, resulting in the inherent ability to levitate and perform vertical takeoff and landing.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] This contrasts with the heavier-than-air aerodynes that primarily use aerodynamic lift, which must have consistent airflow over an aerofoil (wing) surface to stay airborne.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The term has also been used in a narrower sense, to refer to the statically tethered balloon in contrast to the free-flying airship.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] This article uses the term in its broader sense.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] An *aerodyne* is a heavier-than-air aircraft that relies on aerodynamic lift, or upthrust produced by the airflow, to fly.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Aerodynes include rotorcraft, airplanes, gliders, and several other varieties of aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Airplanes use wings, or airfoils, to direct the airflow to produce lift.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Wings are usually constructed with a wooden or metal inner framework, and a skin stretched over it.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Rotorcraft use a rotor which acts like a rotating wing, allowing them to hover in place.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] When aerodynes carry a payload, it is usually carried inside the aircraft's fuselage, or central structure, but aerodynes can also carry loads attached outside the aircraft or inside the wing.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Unlike aerostats, which control their altitude by changing their weight, aerodynes use control surfaces to control their altitude, or raise or lower the lift on their wing by adjusting their speed.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] As they typically travel at higher speeds than aerostats, most aerodynes have a rigid structure consisting of a frame covered by a skin.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Powered aircraft are typically powered by internal combustion engines (piston or turbine) burning fossil fuels—typically gasoline (avgas) or jet fuel.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] A very few are powered by rocket power, ramjet propulsion, or by electric motors, or by internal combustion engines of other types, or using other fuels.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] A very few have been powered, for short flights, by human muscle energy (e.g.: Gossamer Condor).
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The avionics comprise any *electronic* aircraft flight control systems and related equipment, including electronic cockpit instrumentation, navigation, radar, monitoring, and communications systems.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The flight envelope of an aircraft refers to its approved design capabilities in terms of airspeed, load factor and altitude.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The maximal total *range* is the maximum distance an aircraft can fly between takeoff and landing.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Powered aircraft range is limited by the aviation fuel energy storage capacity (chemical or electrical) considering both weight and volume limits.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Unpowered aircraft range depends on factors such as cross-country speed and environmental conditions.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The range can be seen as the cross-country ground speed multiplied by the maximum time in the air.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The fuel time limit for powered aircraft is fixed by the available fuel (considering reserve fuel requirements) and the rate of consumption.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The Airbus A350-900ULR is among the longest range airliners.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Some aircraft can gain energy while airborne through the environment (e.g. collecting solar energy or through rising air currents from mechanical or thermal lifting) or from in-flight refueling.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] These aircraft could theoretically have an infinite range.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Control systems adjust the orientation of a vehicle about its CG.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] A control system includes control surfaces which, when deflected, generate a moment (or couple from ailerons) about the cg which rotates the aircraft in pitch, roll, and yaw.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] For example, a pitching moment comes from a force applied at a distance forward or aft of the cg, causing the aircraft to pitch up or down.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] A fixed-wing aircraft increases or decreases the lift generated by the wings when it pitches nose up or down by increasing or decreasing the angle of attack (AOA).
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The roll angle is also known as bank angle on a fixed-wing aircraft, which usually "banks" to change the horizontal direction of flight.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] A fixed wing is typically unstable in pitch, roll, and yaw.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Pitch and yaw stabilities of conventional fixed wing designs require horizontal and vertical stabilisers, which act similarly to the feathers on an arrow.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] These stabilizing surfaces allow equilibrium of aerodynamic forces and to stabilise the flight dynamics of pitch and yaw.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] In fixed-wing aircraft, multiple control surfaces are used to adjust the aircraft's roll, pitch, and yaw.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Ailerons, hinged surfaces normally located on the rear edge of the wing, can raise or lower the lift produced by one side of the wing, causing the aircraft to bank to one side.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Elevators, usually located in the horizontal stabilizer, are used to increase or decrease the lift produced by the tail, causing the aircraft to pitch upwards or downwards, which in turn affects the lift of the wing.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] However, when the ailerons are used to turn an aircraft to the left, the right aileron must be tilted downwards, producing more drag than the left aileron and causing the aircraft to yaw right.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] To counteract this force, most fixed-wing aircraft have a rudder mounted on the vertical stabilizer which can deflect the airflow to the tail left or right to control the aircraft's yaw.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] In rotorcraft, control is mainly accomplished through the cyclical tilting of the rotor's blades, increasing the angle of attack of the blades on one side and decreasing the angle of attack on the other.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Similarly to the rudder on fixed-wing aircraft, rotorcraft with powered rotors have a tail rotor, which counters the rotational thrust produced by the rotor and allows the aircraft to turn in forward flight.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Rotorcraft with unpowered rotors, such as autogyros, use a rudder for yaw.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Aircraft engines produce gases, noise, and particulates from fossil fuel combustion, raising environmental concerns over their global effects and on local air quality.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Jet airliners contribute to climate change by emitting carbon dioxide (CO2), the best understood greenhouse gas, and, with less scientific understanding, nitrogen oxides, contrails and particulates.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Their radiative forcing is estimated at 1.4 that of CO2 alone, excluding induced cirrus cloud with a very low level of scientific understanding.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] In 2018, global commercial operations generated 2.4% of CO2 emissions.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Jet airliners have become more fuel efficient and CO2 emissions per revenue ton-kilometer (RTK) in 2018 were 47% of those in 1990.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] In 2018, CO2 emissions averaged 88 grams of CO2 per revenue passenger per km.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] While the aviation industry is more fuel efficient, overall emissions have risen as the volume of air travel has increased.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] By 2020, aviation emissions were 70% higher than in 2005 and they could grow by 300% by 2050.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Aircraft noise pollution disrupts sleep, children's education and could increase cardiovascular risk.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Airports can generate water pollution due to their extensive handling of jet fuel and deicing chemicals if not contained, contaminating nearby water bodies.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Aviation activities emit ozone and ultrafine particles, both of which are health hazards.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Piston engines used in general aviation burn Avgas, releasing toxic lead.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Aviation's environmental footprint can be reduced by better fuel economy in aircraft, or air traffic control and flight routes can be optimized to lower non-CO2 effects on climate from NOx, particulates or contrails.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Aviation biofuel, emissions trading and carbon offsetting, part of the ICAO's CORSIA, can lower CO2 emissions.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Aviation usage can be lowered by short-haul flight bans, train connections, personal choices and aviation taxation and subsidies.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Fuel-powered aircraft may be replaced by hybrid electric aircraft and electric aircraft or by hydrogen-powered aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Since 2021, the IATA members plan to achieve net-zero carbon emissions by 2050, followed by the ICAO in 2022.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] A military aircraft is any aircraft that is operated by a legal or insurrectionary armed service of any type.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Although scheduled air transport is the larger operation in terms of passenger numbers, GA is larger in the number of flights (and flight hours, in the U.S.) In the U.S., GA carries 166 million passengers each year, more than any individual airline, though less than all the airlines combined.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Since 2004, the U.S. airlines combined have carried over 600 million passengers each year, and in 2014, they carried a combined 662,819,232 passengers.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] All scheduled air transport is commercial, but general aviation can be either commercial or private.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Normally, the pilot, aircraft, and operator must all be authorized to perform commercial operations through separate commercial licensing, registration, and operation certificates.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] An *experimental aircraft* is an aircraft intended for testing new aerospace technologies and design concepts.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The term *research aircraft* or *testbed aircraft*, by contrast, generally denotes aircraft modified to perform scientific studies, such as weather research or geophysical surveying, similar to a research vessel.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] The term "experimental aircraft" also has specific legal meaning in Australia, the United States and some other countries; usually used to refer to aircraft flown with an experimental certificate.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] In the United States, this also includes most homebuilt aircraft, many of which are based on conventional designs and hence are experimental only in name because of certain restrictions in operation.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Model aircraft are typically small-scale replicas of flying aircraft, or new designs built smaller than most passenger aircraft.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Static model aircraft, which cannot fly, are usually not considered to be aircraft, but they can be used to test aspects of a flying aircraft, such as its aerodynamics.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Flying models are commonly propelled by electric motors, combustion engines, or are gliders, but there are many alternate methods of propulsion, such as wound rubber bands and small jet engines.
[src:aerodynamics/aircraft] Most flying model aircraft are either radio-controlled aircraft, fly freely, or are controlled by wires held by the pilot.
